t) convinced the unfriendly state legislature to grant him unilateral power to make budget cuts and unveiled $343 million in cuts to cities, healthcare, and state agencies. this fiscal discipline continued in 2004, in which (candidate last) continued to slash 'nearly every part of state government' to close a $3 billion deficit." (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p><p>- <b> <em>the weekly standard</em>'s terry eastland:</b> "as governor, (candidate last) has scored another turnaround, conservative in both ends and means. told during the campaign that he would inherit a deficit of between $500 million and $1.5 billion, (candidate last) discovered upon taking office a $650 million deficit in fiscal 2003 and an anticipated one of $3 billion in fiscal 2004. (candidate last) balanced the 2003 budget, and he finished 2004 with a $700 million surplus. a reviving economy helped, but (candidate last) didn't tax or borrow, and he reduced spending through government consolidation and reform." (terry eastland, "in 2008, will it be mormon in america?" <em>the weekly standard</em>, 6/6/05) </p></blockquote> <p><b>governor (candidate last) successfully consolidated and restructured several government agencies.</b> "to his credit, (candidate last) attempted to cut down on government spending by streamlining many duplicative and wasteful elements of beacon hill. ... governor (candidate last) successfully consolidated the social service and public health bureaucracy and restructured the metropolitan district commission. (candidate last) even eliminated half of the executive branch's press positions, saving $1.2 million. " (the club for growth, "(candidate full)'s record on economic issues," press release, 8/21/07) </p><p><b>governor (candidate last) left office with a $2 billion rainy-day fund.</b> "'i cut out of the budget over $425 million in spending i thought the state couldn't afford,' (candidate last) said of his final budget as governor. he left office with a $2 billion rainy-day fund." (philip elliott, "(candidate last) hammers anti-tax message," <em>the associated press</em>, 10/7/07) <br/>governor (candidate last) "vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars in spending": </p><p><b>for all four of the fiscal-year budgets that crossed his desk, governor (candidate last) used the line-item veto power more than 800 times.</b> over the course of four budgets, governor (candidate last) made over 300 line-item reductions, 350 line-item eliminations and struck language 150 times. (chapter 26 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2003, governor's veto message, 6/30/03; chapter 149 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2004, governor's veto message, 6/25/04; chapter 45 of the commonwealth of massachusetts acts of 2005, governor's veto message, 6/30/05;governor (candidate full), memo to the senate and house of representatives of the commonwealth of massachusetts; fiscal year 2007 general appropriations act veto items: line item accounts, 7/8/06) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p>- <b>beacon hill institute executive director david terck: "he vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars in spending."</b> wall street journal's paul gigot: "one of the criticisms of president bush is that's he's been unwilling to use his veto pen to reign in spending. was governor (candidate last) willing to use his veto pen to do that in massachusetts?" beacon hill institute executive director david terck: "he most certainly was. he vetoed hundreds of millions of dollars in spending." (fox news' "journal editorial report," 3/31/07) </p></blockquote> <p><b> <u>governor (candidate last) has a record of fighting for lower taxes in massachusetts:</u> </b> </p><p><b>the club for growth: governor (candidate last)'s record includes "solid efforts to promote pro-growth tax policy."</b> "that said, governor (candidate last)'s single term contained some solid efforts to promote pro-growth 